munist, however, he was twice imprisoned for a total of sixteen years.Both a memoir and a documentary history of the Chinese revolution from 1949 through the Cultural Revolution, The Man Who Stayed Behind provides a human perspective on China's efforts to build a new society. Critical of both his own mistakes and those of the Communist leadership, Rittenberg nevertheless gives an even-handed account of a country that is now free of internal war for the first time in a hundred years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCommunistszChinaxHistoryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh1 aBennett, Amanda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHunt, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallace, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallace, Mike08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383161zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383161423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822383161.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles